{{Multiple issues| {{more citations needed|date=April 2011}} {{weasel words|date=April 2011}} }} {{Infobox theatre | name = The Louisville Palace | image = LouisvillePalaceFullSign.jpg | image_size = 300px | image_alt = | caption = Front view of The Louisville Palace | image_map = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_map_caption= | address = 625 S. 4th Street | city = [[Louisville, Kentucky]] | country = [[United States]] | designation = | owner = [[Live Nation Entertainment]] | tenant = | operator = | capacity = 2,700 | type = | opened = September 1, 1928 | reopened = | yearsactive = | rebuilt = | closed = | demolished = | othernames = | production = | currentuse = [[music venue]] | website = {{URL|http://louisvillepalace.com}} {{Infobox NRHP | embed = yes | name = Loew's and United Artists State Theatre | nrhp_type = | coordinates = {{coord|38|14|51.65|N|85|45|27.62|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Kentucky#USA | area = | built =1927 | architect= Eberson, John | architecture= Other | added = March 28, 1978 | governing_body = Private | refnum=78001361 <ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref> }} }} '''The Louisville Palace''' (also known as the '''Palace Theatre''') is a music venue in [[downtown Louisville|downtown]] [[Louisville, Kentucky]], located in the city's theater district, on the east side of Fourth Street, between Broadway and Chestnut Street. It has a [[seating capacity]] of 2,700 people and is owned by [[Live Nation Entertainment|Live Nation]]. The historic landmark opened on September 1, 1928, and was designed by architect [[John Eberson]].<ref name=lpalace>{{cite web|url=http://www.louisvillepalace.com/VenueInfo#history|title=The Louisville Palace Theater|publisher=Live Nation Worldwide, Inc.}}</ref> It was originally known as the Loew's and United Artists State theatre.
''The Palace'' exhibits a [[Spanish Baroque architecture|Spanish Baroque]] motif with [[arcade (architecture)|arcade]]s, [[balconies]] and [[turret]]s. [[Cobalt blue]], bursts of red and gold indirectly light all of the niches, coves and entrances. Above is a curved, [[vaulted ceiling]] with 139 sculptures of the faces of historical figures. The theater room inside ''The Palace'' is heavily ornamented and displays an imitation nighttime sky on the ceiling.
The theater is two [[storey|stories]] with a floor and a balcony. Both floors contain [[bar (counter)|bar]]s that run the width of the building behind the theater, separated by a grand lobby of intricate art and architecture.
Although the exterior had fallen behind the interior, the Palace was re-dedicated in 1994 and is now a premiere venue.<ref name=lpalace/>
Its uncommon appearance has made it a popular venue for musicians to record live performances (including [[Third Day]] & [[Alison Krauss]]). On June 2, 1983, [[A Flock Of Seagulls]] performed at the Palace and the show was recorded for broadcast by NBC's [[The Source]]. The theatre features an array of popular [[film|movie]]s, old and new, as well as concerts by popular artists.
